    "boxscore_url": "https://www.charlotte49ers.com/sports/baseball/stats/2026/south-carolina/boxscore/19755",
    "recap_url": "https://www.charlotte49ers.com/news/2026/3/17/baseball-seven-run-fifth-propels-niners-past-gamecocks",
    "recap_headline": "Charlotte",
    "recap_text": "COLUMBIA, S.C. \u2013\nTodd Hudson\nwas the key man at the plate for the second game in a row for Charlotte Baseball, hitting a grand slam to put the 49ers in front for good in an 11-8 victory over South Carolina on Tuesday (March 17).\nCharlotte (14-6) trailed South Carolina (12-10) by four early, but erased the deficit and took the lead with a seven-run fifth inning and never looked back. Hudson's grand slam capped off the crooked number and came with the game tied 5-5, after two runs in the fourth and three earlier in the fifth before Hudson's homer.\nOnly the first run of the big inning for the 49ers was charged as an earned run to the Gamecocks as an error with two outs allowed the inning to continue and the final six runs to score. The misplay was one of five errors in the game for South Carolina, with all but three runs going unearned to the Gamecock pitchers. The generosity of the hosts didn't stop with the errors as Charlotte drew 11 walks at the plate and was hit twice for the second-most free passes taken in a game this season.\nThe win is Charlotte's second against an ACC/SEC opponent this season and extends the 49ers winning streak to four straight wins over South Carolina, with three of those coming in Columbia.\nHudson's grand slam was one of two hits in the game for him for his second consecutive game with multiple hits. He was one of four Niners with multiple knocks on the day, joining\nCody Gunderson\n,\nRobert Nedry\n, and\nCale Stricklin\n.\nDawson Bryce\nstretched a single into a double for Charlotte's only other hit in the game, extending his hitting streak to 13 straight games.\nAlec DeMartino\nand\nDylan Koontz\ndidn't record a hit but they both walked three times, tying Charlotte's season-high for most bases on balls by an individual player in a single game this year.\nChayse Oxborrow\nmade his third start on the mound in the last five games for CLT and struck out three batters in the first 2.1 innings of a no-decision.\nJoseph Taylor\nwas the first arm to follow out of the bullpen and logged his third win of the season as the pitcher in the game when the Niners hung the seven on the board in the fifth.\nAndrew Kribbs\nand\nChase Carson\nfollowed Taylor before the Green and White turned to\nAdam Stanton\nto finish it out.\nStanton steadied the ship after things got hairy in the sixth, getting all three outs while keeping the Niners in front with a one-run lead. He came back out for the final three frames as well, only giving up one hit and one walk while punching out five batters to notch a four-inning save.\nHOW IT HAPPENED\nBoth teams' starters fared well in the first two innings, getting through the lineup the first time around without much trouble. That changed when South Carolina's lineup flipped over for the second time through as the Gamecocks opened the scoring with four runs on five hits in the third inning.\nThe Niners got two of the runs back in the fourth, loading the bases up to cut the deficit in half. DeMartino drew a walk to start the inning before moving into scoring position on a single by Gunderson. An infield single followed from Nedry after he beat the throw to first from the shortstop, setting up a sacrifice fly from\nAdrian Jimenez\nto get the Niners on the board. Stricklin was the next batter and put one back up the middle to plate Gunderson from second. Nedry and Stricklin both moved into scoring position on a groundout to the right side but a popup to short ended CLT's hopes of adding more.\nSouth Carolina responded with one in the home half of the fourth inning to extend its lead back to three runs, but Charlotte's big inning followed, flipping the script of the game completely.\nKoontz drew a walk with one out and then came home from first on a two-out double to the wall in right-center by Gunderson. A can of corn to shallow left looked like it was going to end the inning with only one run across but the South Carolina shortstop dropped the ball, allowing Gunderson to score and Nedry on base to keep the inning going. Three straight walks loaded the bases and brought the tying run home before Hudson powered one out the other way for the go-ahead grand slam into Charlotte's bullpen to make it 9-5.\nThree more walks to start the sixth inning loaded them up for the Niners yet again, but Charlotte couldn't do anything with the runners, leaving them loaded.\nThe walk-bug jumped dugouts during the changeover in the sixth as Charlotte suddenly lost the ability to find the zone. Four consecutive walks were issued by three different pitchers to bring a run across for the home team, followed by a failed double play attempt that ended up scoring two runs when the relay throw got away from Gunderson at first, making it a one-run game.\nCharlotte couldn't get any insurance runs in the seventh, but it didn't matter as Stanton found his groove, sitting the side down in order after the stretch. He was rewarded by another run of breathing room in the eighth, with the third error of the game for the Gamecocks bringing Charlotte's 10th run of the game home.\nThe miscues for the hosts continued in the final frame, with CLT's final run scoring from two more South Carolina errors, letting Bryce move up to third on an errant throw to second on a stolen base attempt. The pitch on Bryce's stolen base attempt from first ended up being ball four, nullifying the attempt and creating confusion in the field as the South Carolina infielders let up on the play while the catcher still fired to second, with the throw sailing into the outfield untouched. The Gamecocks tried to pick off pinch runner\nJuan Rivera\nat first to put two outs on the board, but the throw from the mound was wild and allowed Bryce to score from third.\nStanton returned to the hill to close the game out and did just that after allowing the lead-off man to reach. A single put the potential tying run on deck for South Carolina, but Stanton got the three outs he needed with only five more pitches to extend the Niners' winning streak to four straight over the Gamecocks.\nUP NEXT\nCharlotte is back in action on Wednesday (March 18) at Hayes Stadium against USC Upstate. Originally scheduled to start at 6 p.m., the game was moved up to a 4 p.m. first pitch due to forecasted temperatures."
